<h2 id="head-ff11f0da0a4cd245270f188d8a7299b4084d0328">Chatter</h2>
<p>
<strong>Bandobras</strong>: 1. I would like to add a section for bug reports for 2.x.x that have patches included (either by the submitter, or possibly also by someone else later on). There are at least two such bug reports now, I'm testing the patches, they seem to work, but I have trouble finding the bug reports to report on the results of testing. I guess providing patches is a good idea; a separate section would encourage this, help people in using and testing the patches, help maintainers in quickly fixing the patched bugs, etc. If there is no objection I will add the section, in a week or so, and move the patched bugs there. What do you think? 
</p>
<p>
Now I see, some bug reports with fixes have the {fix included} flag, but not all. And I wonder if only bug reports with patches should be in the proposed section or with fixes in other adequate form. I guess I would prefer to include any readable fixes that work for the author  and not only strictly pathes. Or does the {fix included} flag suffice? Should I just flag some more errors and hope people will start flagging themselves? 
</p>

    <ul>

 <strong>Bandobras</strong>: Having heard no objections, I'm just in the process of marking bugs with {fix included}. I'm at <a href="./BugReport/BugReport102">BugReport102</a>. Inside the <a href="./BugReport/BugReport67">BugReport67</a> I have found a discussion about patches section on the Wiki that I do not understand. I guess I will not do anything more than finishing the bug marking, until I can figure out what the noble Developers' policy on the patches is. :) But if <a href="./NeilStevens">NeilStevens</a> could add in the preamble something like "Mark the bugs with a working fix by {fix included}" I guess it wouldn't hurt, would it? 
    </ul>


<p>
<strong>Bandobras</strong>: 2. By the way, some bug reports have the *spoiler* flag, while almost all are spoily. Perhaps the developers could warn about spoilers at the top of this page and discourage the use of this flag? 
</p>

    <ul>

 <strong><a href="./RedNaga">RedNaga</a></strong>: i agree with this. Even those bugs that aren't spoily to begin with often becomes spoily as discussion grow about them, and rarely someone remember to get back to the main (this) page and add the spoiler flag. <p>
 <strong><a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a></strong>: I agree that bug discussions can become spoily, so I added the warning. I'll leave it to Neil as to whether he wants to discontinue the flags. (I do tend to think that end-game related things, at the very least, should still be marked. *shrug*) 
</p>
<p>
 While we are at it, I should point out that many, many people are failing to observe <a href="./NeilStevens">NeilStevens</a>'s injunction to <em>never assume the reader of the full Bug Report page has read this page first.</em> Please put the game version information (and module information, if any), etc., into your bug report. 
</p>

    </ul>


<hr size="3">
 <p>
<strong><a href="./NeilStevens">NeilStevens</a></strong>: Let's not start adding new flags.  Who exactly benefits from a "fix included" flag, for example?  As for spoilers, I'd rather we keep marking them, and especially  I'd rather that people take the time and effort needed to honor those flags, and OMIT SPOILERS where possible. 
</p>
<p>
We don't do patch testing here.  We do bugfix testing via whole-game CVS build releases.  This page has one purpose: bug reporting.  Overloading it with testing is unnecessary and therefore wrong. 
</p>
<p>
I will be removing the {fix included} flags unless someone convinces me not to, and basically only someone with CVS write access could give me a good reason not to. 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a></strong>: Neil: Do you wish people who have fixes to include them here, even if unflagged? If you don't want them to include fixes here but still want the input, where should such fixes be sent? 
</p>
<p>
I guess what I am suggesting is this: Let's not assume that every reader of this page understands the CVS system. Maybe put a simple, short message at the top of the page which informs people who want to offer fixes how they can best do so? 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./NeilStevens">NeilStevens</a></strong>: Fixes are welcome here, but they are only useful to one small group of people: those who have the write access to the source repository.  Patches can be stored here or sent to the mailing list. 
</p>
<p>
The system isn't broken as far as I can see.  Patches are stored here just as bug reports are, and when someone with source repository access gets the time and interest in browsing for bugs to fix, he'll find the bugs and the patches, and deal with them. 
</p>
<p>
What problems do others see with the current system?  Is it thought that adding a "fix included" tag, that developers will spontaneously come and apply them?    What's keeping those from being applied isn't visibility, though.  It's the lack of a developer who is committed to finding and applying those fixes.  Massimiliano Marangio used to do that, but he disappeared a few months ago.   I used to do it long before that, but then I started maintaining the CVS mailing list script, my own modules, the ToME 2.2 and 2.3 series, and now the wiki. 
</p>
<p>
<strong>Bandobras</strong>: I'm sorry to hear there are problems (I mean with people disappearing and overworked). And the problems seem quite natural, for a volunteer work. By the way, thank you all for your work. So kind and so professional. 
</p>
<p>
What I see here, patches and flags and all the fuss, is a grass-root movement to sidestep the problems. No to supplant you, but to thrive despite the problems. We try to help one another by posting fixes, using them, testing, giving feedback, encouragement. If you happen to benefit from such a grass-root movement --- as I hoped --- great! If not, why not help us? If we do something suboptimally, why not show a better way? I mean we are playing in your garden, but you set up the garden just for us to play, didn't you? 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./NeilStevens">NeilStevens</a></strong>: Of course, I don't look to dictate policy in general.  I generally only step in when I think there's something happening that threatens the future  growth and maintainability of the wiki.  Adding flags to bug reports is an example of that.  I used to maintain the flags on the bugs on the forum, so I know from experience that it's no good. 
</p>
<p>
Do you really think that users are applying patches on their own? 
</p>
<p>
<strong>Bandobras</strong>: Well, I do apply patches. Whom else? 
</p>
<p>
Obviously those several people that post patches, apply them, as well. I'm not sure, though, if they do so with other people's patches, or only with their own. Repackagers for Linux distributions may also apply patches (Debian packages of many programs come with numerous patches, some of them of bugs not yet fixed upstream, most of the bugs reported on bugs@debian). This is, because volunteer work is jerky --- this is normal. Upstream can be sluggish and people have to cope with it. And they do, to everyone's benefit.  
</p>
<p>
I used to compile from CVS after every nontrivial change. Then CVS had frozen. Then I lost and Ent Sorceror to the dark arena bug (see my ditl), then I stopped playing and waited for the CVS, then I found a patch on another ditl and applied it myself and seeing that's easy I also applied some more. I guess if the CVS is dead much longer, more people might go the same way. For those with no expertise there may even appear links to unofficial, patched binaries.  
</p>
<p>
Don't understand me wrongly: I have never, for a moment, been angry that the CVS is frozen. The opposite: I felt and I feel sorry, if not guilty, I have no time (and no skill comparable to yours) to help with the project myself, especially seeing there is a need. But I have been able to help myself and I tried to share this with others. Perhaps the flags are bad (but they are voluntary and to be only assigned by submitters, not admins). So, perhaps give write access for more people exclusively for some exotic branches of CVS (I'm not sure this is possible with CVS, though)? Or a section on the WIKI with patches? Or perhaps tome2 is so stable, mature and old, there will never be unofficial binaries and people will live happily with dark arenas for the next 10 years. OK, so I may be wrong. But then, what when tome3 comes out?  
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./NeilStevens">NeilStevens</a></strong>: Hmmm, you paint a really bleak picture of ToME 2 since Massimiliano disappeared.  
</p>

        <ul>

  <strong>Bandobras</strong>: You've just been spoiling us for so long with frequent updates, and now you just pay the price. ;) 
        </ul>


<p>
OK, let them stay, at least until we get someone who starts applying patches again. 
</p>

        <ul>

  <strong>Bandobras</strong>: I would be glad to complete the initial marking, for a good start, if I knew there is an encouragement for people to mark their own bugs in the header of this page, as I proposed. But, as you see, I'm not in a hurry, and if there is no support for my initiative from other people, I will just as gladly do nothing :), or even wipe the few flags I've already added. 
        </ul>


<p>
As for CVS, it's not frozen.  It's just that nobody is doing the work.  And if someone stepped up and was willing to start fixing bugs, he could get write access pretty quick, I think.  There are no worries about limited access. 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./TheFalcon">TheFalcon</a></strong>: Shouldn't the modules have separate fixed bug sections?(at least for Theme) i.e. put the Theme solved bugs next to the report ones, rather than have them lower down. 
</p>
</div><div id="footer">


